text.tspan: MIR User Studies through the Lens of Relevance
Promoting the Impact of MIR User Research
David M. Weigl, Joan C. Bartlett, Daniel Steele, Catherine Guastavino

flowRoot.flowPara: School of Information Studies, McGill University, Canada Oxford e-Research Centre, University of Oxford, UK

text.tspan: Challenges limiting the impact of MIR user studies (as per Lee & Cunningham, 2013)
Limitations of sample size and sampling strategy challenge generalizability
Difficulty of systematic synthesis due to highly diffuse publication venues
Fast changing nature of the MIR field, user behaviours, and expectations
Disconnect between user researchers and system / evaluation task designers
How have we addressed these challenges?
Triangulate findings of different studies using a shared conceptual framework
Reuse Lee & Cunningham's list of 159 articles for our systematic analysis
Encourage MIR user researchers to contribute new findings to our corpus
Provide access to all findings, queryable according to design task descriptors
Size of our corpus as per ISMIR LBD 2016

flowRoot.flowPara: Saracevic's stratified model of relevance interactions
"The creation of rigorous and practicable theories concerning the nature of experiential similarity and relevance is the single most important challenge facing MIR researchers today."
... yet formal consideration of relevance in MIR has remained scarce
Relevance is a, if not even the, key notion in information science in general and information retrieval in particular.
